<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Pinot Noir's Weight to Your Protein</strong> - Light-bodied Pinot Noirs from cooler climates like Oregon's Willamette Valley pair beautifully with salmon, duck breast, or pork tenderloin, while fuller-bodied examples from California's Russian River Valley can handle lamb or beef short ribs. The wine's natural acidity and moderate tannins complement the richness without overwhelming delicate proteins.</li>

  <li><strong>Embrace Earthy Flavors and Mushrooms</strong> - Pinot Noir's signature earthy undertones, derived from compounds like geosmin in the soil, create magical pairings with mushroom-based dishes. Try coq au vin with chanterelles, truffle risotto, or even a simple mushroom pizza. The wine's earthiness amplifies these flavors rather than competing with them.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Slightly Cooler Than Most Reds</strong> - Pour Pinot Noir at 60-65°F to preserve its delicate fruit aromatics and prevent alcohol from dominating. This cooler temperature enhances the wine's natural acidity, making it more food-friendly and allowing subtle flavors in dishes like herb-crusted rack of lamb or duck confit to shine through.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip the Decanting for Most Bottles</strong> - Unlike Cabernet Sauvignon, most Pinot Noirs don't benefit from decanting due to their delicate structure and lighter tannins. Exception: aged Burgundies (10+ years) may need 30 minutes to open up. For food pairing, this means you can open and pour immediately, making Pinot Noir perfect for spontaneous dinner pairings.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Large-Bowled Burgundy Glasses</strong> - Pinot Noir's complex aromatics—from red cherry and raspberry to violet and spice—need space to develop. A proper Burgundy glass concentrates these delicate scents at your nose, enhancing the pairing experience with aromatic dishes like herb-roasted chicken or grilled salmon with fresh herbs.</li>

  <li><strong>Consider the Wine's Regional Style for Sauce Selection</strong> - Burgundian Pinot Noirs with higher acidity pair excellently with cream-based sauces and butter-rich dishes, while New World versions with riper fruit complement tomato-based sauces and barbecue glazes. The wine's origin directly impacts which flavors will harmonize or clash.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Your Drinking Window</strong> - Most Pinot Noirs are best consumed within 3-7 years of vintage when their fresh fruit flavors complement lighter fare like grilled vegetables or seared tuna. However, aged examples develop tertiary flavors of leather and forest floor that pair magnificently with game birds, wild mushroom dishes, and aged cheeses.</li>

  <li><strong>Leverage Pinot Noir's Natural Food-Friendliness</strong> - Pinot Noir's moderate alcohol (typically 12.5-14%), bright acidity, and silky tannins make it one of the most versatile food wines. It won't overpower delicate dishes like pan-seared scallops, yet has enough structure for heartier fare like braised short ribs. This versatility makes it ideal for multi-course meals where you want one wine throughout.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What meats pair best with Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Duck, lamb, and pork are the classic triumvirate for Pinot Noir, as their rich flavors complement the wine's earthy undertones and moderate tannins. Game birds like quail and pheasant also excel with aged Burgundy, while lighter preparations of beef tenderloin work beautifully with more structured Oregon or California Pinots. The key is matching the wine's intensity to the preparation method—grilled meats for bolder New World styles, roasted or braised for elegant Old World expressions.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you pair Pinot Noir with fish and seafood?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—salmon, tuna, and other meaty fish are outstanding with Pinot Noir, especially when grilled or prepared with mushroom-based sauces. The wine's moderate tannins won't overpower delicate seafood, while its acidity brightens rich preparations. Avoid pairing with very light white fish or raw preparations, as these lack the substance to stand up to even the most delicate Pinot Noir.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What vegetables and mushrooms work with Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Earthy mushrooms like shiitake, porcini, and morels create magical pairings with Pinot Noir's natural forest floor aromatics and umami complexity. Root vegetables such as roasted beets, carrots, and parsnips complement the wine's earthiness, while grilled eggplant and roasted tomatoes enhance its fruit-forward characteristics. These ingredients work especially well in risottos, gratins, or as accompaniments to meat dishes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve different foods with Burgundy versus New World Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes—traditional Burgundy's higher acidity and mineral-driven profile pairs beautifully with classic French preparations like coq au vin, beef bourguignon, and herb-crusted lamb. New World Pinots, with their riper fruit and often higher alcohol, handle bolder flavors like barbecued meats, spice-rubbed dishes, and tomato-based sauces more successfully. Consider the wine's specific characteristics rather than just the grape variety when planning your menu.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What cheeses complement Pinot Noir best?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Soft-ripened cheeses like Brie and Camembert are classic matches, as their creamy texture balances Pinot Noir's tannins while their earthy rinds echo the wine's mushroom notes. Gruyère, aged Gouda, and Comté work wonderfully with more structured Pinots, while fresh goat cheese brightens lighter styles. Avoid very strong blue cheeses, which can overwhelm the wine's delicate fruit characteristics.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What common mistakes should I avoid when pairing food with Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is treating all Pinot Noirs the same—a delicate Sancerre Rouge requires different pairings than a powerful Russian River Valley bottling. Avoid overly spicy dishes that mask the wine's subtle aromatics, and steer clear of very acidic sauces (like heavy vinaigrettes) that can make the wine taste flat. Also, don't automatically default to red meat; Pinot Noir's versatility shines with thoughtful vegetarian and seafood pairings.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Pinot Noir good for beginners learning food and wine pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Pinot Noir is excellent for beginners because its moderate tannins and bright acidity make it forgiving with many foods, while its complexity teaches important pairing principles. Start with classic combinations like roasted chicken with mushrooms or grilled salmon, then experiment with the wine's affinity for earthy flavors and umami-rich dishes. Its transparency to terroir and vintage variation also helps develop palate sensitivity to how wine characteristics influence food compatibility.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve Pinot Noir with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Pinot Noir slightly cooler than other red wines, around 60-65°F (15-18°C), to preserve its delicate aromatics and prevent the alcohol from overwhelming food flavors. This temperature enhances the wine's natural acidity, making it more food-friendly and allowing subtle flavors to shine through. Lighter styles like Sancerre Rouge can go even cooler, around 55°F (13°C), while powerful California Pinots benefit from the warmer end of the range.</p>
  </div>
